'''Arthur Harry Church''' [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]<ref name="frs">{{Cite journal | last1 = Tansley | first1 = A. G. | authorlink = Arthur Tansley| title = Arthur Harry Church. 1865-1937 | doi = 10.1098/rsbm.1939.0001 | journal = [[Obituary Notices of Fellows of the Royal Society]] | volume = 2 | issue = 7 | pages = 432–443| year = 1939 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> (28 March 1865 – 24 April 1937) was a British [[botanist]] and botanical illustrator.
==Biography== Church was born in [[Plymouth]], [[England]], the son of a saddler, and went to school locally. In 1887 his mother died and, with his inheritance of £100, he went to [[University College of Wales, Aberystwyth]]. With a first ([[University of London|London]] external) degree in Botany he won in 1891 a scholarship to [[Jesus College, Oxford]], obtaining a first-class [[University of Oxford|Oxford]] degree in botany in 1894.
He was a [[Oxbridge Fellow|Research Fellow]] of Jesus College from 1908 to 1912 and University [[Reader (academic rank)|Reader]] in Botany from 1910 to 1930. He was elected as a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] in 1921.<ref name="frs"/> His particular fields of interest were [[phyllotaxy]], the development and arrangement of parts of the flower and one-celled sea plants.<ref name=Times>{{cite news|title=Dr. A. H. Church An Oxford Botanist|work=[[The Times]] |date=April 29, 1937|page=18}}</ref> He was a fine illustrator and photographer, sometimes illustrating his own publications.<ref name=ODNB>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/38462| title=Church, Arthur Harry (1865–1937)|last=Mabberley |first=D. J. |work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]] |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year=2004|accessdate=2008-07-22}}</ref>
He married Emma Palmer Pratt of [[Aberystwith]]. They had three daughters. Each daughter was given as her middle name the name of a plant in flower at the time of her birth: Audrey Althea ([[hollyhock]]), Rosemary Doronica (''[[Doronicum orientale]]'') and Grace Coryla ([[hazel]]).
